{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3410430,"name":"paulonis","username":"paulonis","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/5fc32e/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-23T01:36:36.043Z","cooked":"<p>With an elevator used for climbing, the load when extending the elevator is approximately the weight of the sliding parts of the elevator.  The load when retracting the elevator is approximately the weight of the robot minus the sliding parts of the elevator.  That’s a substantially different load.  Is it possible to change the linear state-space model inside of the <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/ElevatorSim.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">WPILib ElevatorSim class</a> on the fly to represent the change in the real system that happens at the moment when the elevator finishes extending with no robot load and then begins to retract with the full robot load?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-07-23T01:36:36.043Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":230,"reads":280,"readers_count":279,"score":1206.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":469001,"topic_slug":"simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing","display_username":"paulonis","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/ElevatorSim.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"ElevatorSim (WPILib API 2024.3.2)","clicks":48}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":22261,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing/469001/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3410463,"name":"sam liu","username":"catrix","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/dbc845/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-23T04:21:04.237Z","cooked":"<p>Ok here’s what I think.<br>
Changing the state-space model on the fly is not allowed, you would have to declare an extra elevator sim object <code>simWhenRobotClimbing</code> representing the system when the robot is hooked on the stage.<br>
Notice that, because WPILIB thinks gravity is always downwards, <code>simWhenRobotClimbing</code> will be reversed, because when the robot is hooked, gravity pulls robot down, and therefore pushes the climber up in relative to the robot. Let’s just define the output of <code>simWhenRobotClimbing</code> as the amount of meters that the robot have climbed, which is 0 when the climber module is at its highest position, and increases when the climber module goes down.</p>
<p>I tried to implement this in java, just for fun.  So don’t use it before you test and debug it.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="Java"><code class="lang-Java">package frc.robot.utils;

import edu.wpi.first.math.system.plant.DCMotor;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.simulation.ElevatorSim;

public class ClimberSim extends ElevatorSim {
    private final double ELEVATOR_MIN_HEIGHT_METERS, ELEVATOR_MAX_HEIGHT_METERS;
    private final ElevatorSim simWhenRobotClimbing;
    private boolean isRobotClimbing;
    /**
     * Assumption: robotMassKg &gt; climbModuleMassKg
     * */
    public ClimberSim(DCMotor gearbox, double gearing, double climbModuleMassKg, double robotMassKg, double drumRadiusMeters, double minHeightMeters, double maxHeightMeters) {
        super(gearbox, gearing, climbModuleMassKg, drumRadiusMeters, minHeightMeters, maxHeightMeters, true, minHeightMeters);
        this.simWhenRobotClimbing = new ElevatorSim(
                gearbox, gearing,
                robotMassKg - climbModuleMassKg,
                drumRadiusMeters,
                0, maxHeightMeters-minHeightMeters, // we simulate how much distance the robot have climbed (in comparison to maxHeight) downwards
                true,
                maxHeightMeters-minHeightMeters // the climber is at minHeightMeters in the beginning, so climber simulation is at the highest climbing position
        );
        this.ELEVATOR_MIN_HEIGHT_METERS = minHeightMeters;
        this.ELEVATOR_MAX_HEIGHT_METERS = maxHeightMeters;
    }

    public void startClimb() {
        isRobotClimbing = true;
    }

    public void stopClimb() {
        isRobotClimbing = false;
    }

    public void copyElevatorSimStateToClimberSim() {
        final double CLIMB_POSITION = ELEVATOR_MAX_HEIGHT_METERS - super.getPositionMeters(),
                CLIMB_VELOCITY = -super.getVelocityMetersPerSecond();
        simWhenRobotClimbing.setState(CLIMB_POSITION, CLIMB_VELOCITY);
    }

    public void copyClimberSimStateToElevatorSim() {
        final double ELEVATOR_POSITION = ELEVATOR_MAX_HEIGHT_METERS - simWhenRobotClimbing.getPositionMeters(),
                ELEVATOR_VELOCITY = -simWhenRobotClimbing.getVelocityMetersPerSecond();
        super.setState(ELEVATOR_POSITION, ELEVATOR_VELOCITY);
    }

    @Override
    public void setInputVoltage(double volts) {
        simWhenRobotClimbing.setInputVoltage(-volts);
        super.setInputVoltage(volts);
    }

    @Override
    public void update(double dtSeconds) {
        if (isRobotClimbing) {
            simWhenRobotClimbing.update(dtSeconds);
            copyClimberSimStateToElevatorSim();
        } else {
            super.update(dtSeconds);
            copyElevatorSimStateToClimberSim();
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-07-23T04:21:04.237Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":9,"reads":251,"readers_count":250,"score":115.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":469001,"topic_slug":"simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing","display_username":"sam liu","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":60033,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"CE Student @ UWaterloo | 5516 Alum "},"post_url":"/t/simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing/469001/2","custom_user_title":"CE Student @ UWaterloo | 5516 Alum ","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3410509,"name":"paulonis","username":"paulonis","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/5fc32e/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-23T12:41:21.563Z","cooked":"<p>That is a really practical approach to this problem.  I was hoping that there was a way to modify the discrete-time A and B matrices so the system response would change with time.  Short of that “elegant” way, this approach with parallel models that stay synced in state is pretty genius.  Thanks for this insight.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-07-23T12:41:21.563Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":143,"readers_count":142,"score":28.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":469001,"topic_slug":"simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing","display_username":"paulonis","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":60033,"username":"catrix","name":"sam liu","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/dbc845/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":22261,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing/469001/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3410573,"name":"paulonis","username":"paulonis","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/5fc32e/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-23T16:44:39.515Z","cooked":"<p>The code generously provided almost works.  It appears that the elevator position and velocity aren’t available to getPositionMeters() or getVelocityMetersPerSecond() calls immediately after a setState() call. I had to update the inactive model in the update method to get the synced states to “take”.  I used a very small time interval so the states end up essentially unchanged from the synced values.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    @Override
    public void update(double dtSeconds) {
        if (isRobotClimbing) {
            simWhenRobotClimbing.update(dtSeconds);
            copyClimberSimStateToElevatorSim();
            super.update(0.000001);
        } else {
            super.update(dtSeconds);
            copyElevatorSimStateToClimberSim();
            simWhenRobotClimbing.update(0.000001);
        }
    }
</code></pre>
<p>There may be a more correct way to do this, but this approach is sufficient for my need.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-07-23T16:53:32.502Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":115,"readers_count":114,"score":48.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":469001,"topic_slug":"simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing","display_username":"paulonis","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":22261,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/simulating-an-elevator-used-for-climbing/469001/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3410796,"name":"sam liu","username":"catrix","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/dbc845/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-24T07:09:05.181Z","cooked":"<p>You’re welcome, Congratulations on finally getting it to work! <img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/grin.png?v=12" title=":grin:" class="emoji" alt=":grin:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20"></p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-07-24T07:09:05.181Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":76,"readers_count":75,"score":15.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":469001,"topic_slug":"simulating-an-elevator-used-for-cli